Normalizing Text¶

  • Here are the steps taken to prepare the text for modeling. The process in preparing the data for moedling is called normalizing. Essentially, it prepares to standardize the text so different variations of a word (eat, ate, Eat, eaten) all are viewed the same
    • It seems it has already been converted to lowercase; however, we are looked at only a few documents. Thus, we need to ensure text in all documents are in lower case by converting them. This will prevent the model from viewing words like Pizza differently than pizza.
    • Next, urls in articles are typically contained with a 'www.'. URLs are not helpful in identifying common terms. Therefore, we will remove any of these urls from our text.
    • Third, we need to remove all punctuation and numbers as they can create noise for our model. Puncutation is meant for clarity. It does not provide semantic valuee.
    • Last we need to remove all digits from the model as the variation in numbers gives us very little information.

Tokenazation¶

First, we need to create a method that tokenizes and lemmatizes our string. Tokenzation is the process of taking a string and separate the string into individual words. Separating each word into a list will help us analyze each word individually. After tokenizing the string, we can convert each word into it's base word. This will prevent instances when eats is counted differently than eat.

In [60]:
nltk.download('stopwords')
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
stopwords = set(stopwords.words('english'))

#Add own words to remove from text
custom_words = ['said', 'say', 'ha', 'wa', 'bn', "would", "also", "could"]
stopwords.update(custom_words)


def preprocess(article):
    """
    Method to tokenize and lemmatize string
    """
    new_words = []
    #create a list of all the words in the string
    words = word_tokenize(article)
    
    #remove stopwords
    for word in words:
        if word not in stopwords:
            new_words.append(word)
            
    #convert words to base format
    lemmatized = ' '.join([lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in new_words])
    return lemmatized

Polarity¶

Polarity measures how positive or negative an article viewpoint is. Scores range from -1 to 1. The score is closer to 1 if the article is positive, 0 if neutral and negative if the viewpoint is negative. Overall, all of the articles have a neutral viewpoint. Sports articles tend to have the most positive tone while business articles are the most negative. Overall, this is understanding as many journalists tend to write in a neutral tone. Many journalists believe a swaying tone could lead to credability loss

Subjectivity¶

Subjectivity measures how opinionated a text is. With a range between 0 and 1, a text has a score closer to 1 if it is more opinion based. Subjectivity looks for the occurrence of adverbs. For example, She walked away angrily would have a higher subjectivity score than She walked away. For our data, all 5 categories have a median subjectivity score around 0.4. Thus, all of our articles are slightly opinion-based.

Converting to TF-IDF¶

Next, we need to convert our dataframe into a a model matrix format using TF-IDF. TF-IDF is short for "term frequency - inverse document frequency". Essentially, it is a statistic which evaluates how orignal a word is in a document compared to other documents in the collection. It is calculated by the following:

$$w_{i,j} = tf_{i,j} * log(\frac{N}{df_{i}})$$
  • The terms stand for the following:
    • $tf_{i,j}$
      • the number of occurenced of term i in document j
    • $log(\frac{N}{df_{i}})$
      • the log of the total of the number of documents in the collection divided by the number of doucuments where term $i$ occurs

The higher the TF-IDF score the more rare the document is among the collection. In other words, it helps use identify the originality of the word. Thus, articles that have similar TF-IDF calculations should belong to the same category. We will use this matrix for our final EDA plot and our model.

In [68]:

Again, this is understandable as game could be associated with video game in the tech context; however, game refers to any rugby, soccer, basketball, etc. match. However, the term game* is more often used with sports articles compared to tech; thus, its TF-IDF score is slightly higher in the game category.

Matrix Factorization and Prediction¶

To model our text data, we will use Non-negative Matrix Factorization. This model is most appropriate for text data as it words best with non negative values. Essentially, we choose the number of components we want. This is typically the # of subtopics we care to find. In our case, we have five article topics; therefore, our number of components is defined as 5. NMF essentially takes our matrix of words of words an finds which group of words are highly associated with each other. Since we have 5 components, we are trying to find 5 different subgroups where the words of each subgroups are highly associated with eac other. In our context, 'associated with each other' is just saying they typically appear in the same articles. It does this by dividing the one matrix into two matrices. Thes first matrix (W) holds all the documents and the strength of their relationship with each of the 5 components. The second component, (X), contains each component and their relationship strength with each term from our orginal matrix. Multiplies togther, we get our original term matrix. In this assignment this matrix is called the component matrix. Once given our 5 components, we can find the words highly associated with the 5 components.

Model Evaluation¶

As we can see below, our model did quite well. Overall, it is 92% accurate. Our classes were balanced, thus, accuracy is a good metric in this case. Also, our model has very high recall and precision scores. Precision measures the percentage of times our document is the cateogry we predict it as. Recall measures the percentage of a class we correctly classified as that class. Last, our accuracy score is the same for the test set and the training set; thus, we didn't train our model in a way that overfit the data.

Comparison to Supervised Learning¶

Next, we would like to compare our matrix facotrized model to the Multinomail Naive Bayes model. This model is based off of a well known theorem in statistice: The Baye's Theorem. This theorem calculates conditional probability with the following theorem:

$$P(A|B)= P(A) * P(B|A)P(B)$$

In this case, A is our article category and B is our word. This probability calculation is known as the posterior probability. Our algorithim looks at each word to determine how likely that word would appear in different cateogries. Once the probability is calculated for each word, the algorithm determines the probability a document belongs to each class.The class with the highest probability is what the document is labeled as.

Naive Bayes is a good model for our dataset the dependency assumption works well with our data. Naive Bayes fails when predictors are dependent on other predictors; we assume each term is independent of another. This consitutes the 'Naive' part of the algorithm name.

Overall, our model scored very high. Again, because our classes are fairly balanced, accuracy is good measure on how well our model is doing. Our training data has an accuracy of 98%. Our test model was 96% accurate as shown by the picture below.

In [84]:

Looking at our training results Our precision and recall were all fairly balanced. Our most common misclassifcation was classifying tech articles as business, politics as tech and entertainment as tech.

Overall, the supervised naive bayes model performed similarly to our unspervised algorithm On the other hand, our unsupervised algorithm didn't overfit nearly as much as naive_bayes. Regardless, both models performed fairly well. Also, our dataset is fairly small compared to many other datasets. As stated before, Naive Bayes requires independent predictors. Therefore, a dataset with high dimensionalty would likely create dependences. Thus, as the the numbers of predictors increase our non-matrix factorization would perform better.
